WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:10.500 --> 00:00:14.100
Now you remember from
last week that we're in the

00:00:14.100 --> 00:00:15.500
moment of phasing
out of the 1960s,

00:00:15.500 --> 00:00:21.667
moving into the
1970s, but of course,

00:00:21.667 --> 00:00:23.767
human actions,
inactions, chronology,

00:00:23.767 --> 00:00:26.000
is not simply as
neat as dates on a,

00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:28.367
on a calendar as a
timeline.&nbsp; A lot of the

00:00:28.367 --> 00:00:34.300
social confusion, violence,
and cultural excitement

00:00:34.300 --> 00:00:36.600
actually, of this era,
of the late sixties,

00:00:36.600 --> 00:00:39.900
is right there in the
1970s.&nbsp; And this lecture's

00:00:39.900 --> 00:00:42.500
actually trying to canvass
some of the political

00:00:42.500 --> 00:00:47.567
turmoil and its, its
marriage to popular culture

00:00:47.567 --> 00:00:52.300
in the early 1970s.&nbsp; By
way of context though,

00:00:52.300 --> 00:00:57.900
let me start in the spring
of 1970.&nbsp; On April 30th--and

00:00:57.900 --> 00:01:00.067
actually, let
me focus--it's,

00:01:00.067 --> 00:01:03.300
frankly, just focus on two
weeks in 1970.&nbsp; On April

00:01:03.300 --> 00:01:07.800
30th, President Nixon
announces the invasion of

00:01:07.800 --> 00:01:11.667
Cambodia, escalation of
the war in Southeast Asia in

00:01:11.667 --> 00:01:16.300
general, and the need
for one hundred and fifty

00:01:16.300 --> 00:01:20.800
thousand more troops to
find a lasting peace.

00:01:20.800 --> 00:01:23.000
In response, the campus
at Kent State in Ohio,

00:01:23.000 --> 00:01:29.800
the ROTC building is set
on fire.&nbsp; The Ohio governor

00:01:29.800 --> 00:01:33.367
dispatches National Guard
to make sure that the campus

00:01:33.367 --> 00:01:40.200
remains
peaceful.&nbsp; On to May 4th,

00:01:40.200 --> 00:01:42.300
this attempt to keep
the peace on Kent State

00:01:44.367 --> 00:01:49.000
evaporates, when
twenty-eight Guardsmen open

00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:52.700
fire on Kent State students,
killing four and wounding

00:01:52.700 --> 00:01:59.300
nine.&nbsp;
Immediately--immediately

00:01:59.300 --> 00:02:03.867
being a day--five hundred
colleges are shut down

00:02:03.867 --> 00:02:07.167
across the country, or
they're disrupted from

00:02:07.167 --> 00:02:12.367
protests.&nbsp; Our country,
according to college

00:02:12.367 --> 00:02:18.367
protestors, our country is
now attacking us.&nbsp; It makes

00:02:20.600 --> 00:02:26.467
tremendous
headlines.&nbsp; On May 14th,

00:02:26.467 --> 00:02:28.500
ten days--[student sneezes]
bless you--ten days after

00:02:28.500 --> 00:02:35.000
Kent State, at
Jackson State University,

00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:36.300
a historically
black university,

00:02:36.300 --> 00:02:40.700
during a student protest,
state and highway patrolmen

00:02:40.700 --> 00:02:45.200
open fire with automatic
weapons into dormitories.&nbsp;

00:02:45.200 --> 00:02:47.267
Allegations are that someone
was sniping at them.&nbsp; No

00:02:47.267 --> 00:02:49.600
evidence was
ever found to that,

00:02:49.600 --> 00:02:55.767
to that end.&nbsp; They opened
fire without any warning,

00:02:55.767 --> 00:03:01.400
killed two students and
wounded nine.&nbsp; The scale of

00:03:01.400 --> 00:03:05.700
national attention is
not commensurate with what

00:03:05.700 --> 00:03:09.600
happens at Kent
State.&nbsp; So for,

00:03:09.600 --> 00:03:12.500
in the African
American community,

00:03:12.500 --> 00:03:15.800
there is a sense
that the police state,

00:03:15.800 --> 00:03:18.500
in this case, state
and highway patrolmen,

00:03:18.500 --> 00:03:20.500
could kill our college
students without anybody

00:03:20.500 --> 00:03:23.600
worrying too much,
but at Kent State,

00:03:23.600 --> 00:03:26.700
also inexcusable, that
if you kill the students,

00:03:26.700 --> 00:03:31.100
it becomes a national
catastrophe.&nbsp; Meanwhile,

00:03:31.100 --> 00:03:34.000
in New Haven, just about
two blocks from here--well,

00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:38.700
actually, all throughout
New Haven--the Black Panther

00:03:38.700 --> 00:03:46.467
Party and the FBI are at a
standoff.&nbsp; Black Panther

00:03:46.467 --> 00:03:50.000
Party and fellow travelers
had come to New Haven,

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:55.267
essentially to protest the
murder trial of Bobby Seale,

00:03:55.267 --> 00:03:59.700
who's accused of authorizing
the murder of Alex Rackley,

00:03:59.700 --> 00:04:01.100
member of the
Black Panther Party,

00:04:01.100 --> 00:04:06.600
people believed to have been
an informant to the FBI.&nbsp;

00:04:06.600 --> 00:04:08.700
Fifteen thousand people
descend upon the Green,

00:04:11.567 --> 00:04:15.200
Panthers,
Panther supporters,

00:04:15.200 --> 00:04:17.300
sort of anarchist
hippies, called the Yippies,

00:04:17.300 --> 00:04:21.300
by--led by Abbie Hoffman,
fellow travel--travelers of

00:04:21.300 --> 00:04:24.567
all sorts.&nbsp; And there was a
real fear that the city is

00:04:24.567 --> 00:04:30.100
going to be collapsed into a
race riot.&nbsp; The university,

00:04:30.100 --> 00:04:31.500
under the leadership
of Kingman Brewster,

00:04:31.500 --> 00:04:33.200
the president at the time,
does something that people

00:04:33.200 --> 00:04:36.667
never expected, and actually
opened its doors to the

00:04:36.667 --> 00:04:41.500
Black Panthers.&nbsp; It
created a mechanism,

00:04:41.500 --> 00:04:45.500
it felt--Brewster felt, that
would relieve some of the

00:04:45.500 --> 00:04:52.900
pent-up anxiety and tension
over what's happening around

00:04:52.900 --> 00:04:57.667
the country and then
locally.&nbsp; Classes are

00:04:57.667 --> 00:05:00.200
canceled; there's student
strikes.&nbsp; I think two or

00:05:00.200 --> 00:05:02.800
three pipe bombs go off at
Ingalls Rink.&nbsp; It's a level

00:05:02.800 --> 00:05:09.100
of chaos that you, that
you are not familiar with.&nbsp;

00:05:09.100 --> 00:05:13.067
Kingman Brewster declares
that he actually doubts--and

00:05:13.067 --> 00:05:15.467
I'm paraphrasing
here--whether a black person

00:05:15.467 --> 00:05:19.100
can get a fair trial
anywhere in America.&nbsp;

00:05:19.100 --> 00:05:20.900
Immediately, the
alums start phoning in,

00:05:20.900 --> 00:05:25.067
calling for his resignation,
for his outlandish

00:05:25.067 --> 00:05:28.367
statement.&nbsp; It's
a national event,

00:05:28.367 --> 00:05:34.100
student unrest; it's a local
story as well.&nbsp; In this

00:05:34.100 --> 00:05:41.600
spirit of what's going on in
the country on the college

00:05:41.600 --> 00:05:45.400
campuses, and the
nation, the call for federal

00:05:45.400 --> 00:05:48.300
troops--excuse me, for
more military troops,

00:05:48.300 --> 00:05:53.167
the invasion of Cambodia,
you have an astonishing,

00:05:53.167 --> 00:05:58.867
almost sort of a call
and response by a lot of

00:05:58.867 --> 00:06:02.900
cultural artists.&nbsp; Most
famous in this regard--well,

00:06:06.867 --> 00:06:10.567
most famous to me at least,
in this regard--is Marvin

00:06:10.567 --> 00:06:17.100
Gaye.&nbsp; Marvin Gaye, who had
made a career at Motown by

00:06:17.100 --> 00:06:21.800
piecing together and
performing love songs,

00:06:21.800 --> 00:06:25.300
branches out a year later in
May of 1971 with something

00:06:25.300 --> 00:06:26.800
really quite different.&nbsp;
So he's known for,

00:06:26.800 --> 00:06:30.100
for this: [Marvin
Gaye, Tammi Terrell,

00:06:30.100 --> 00:06:34.800
"Ain't No Mountain High
Enough" excerpt plays.]

00:06:34.800 --> 00:06:38.800
Listen, baby Ain't no mountain
high Ain't no valley low

00:06:38.800 --> 00:06:42.800
Aint no river wide enough,

00:06:42.800 --> 00:06:49.467
baby If you need me, call me
No matter where you are

00:06:49.467 --> 00:06:53.467
No matter how
far Don't worry,

00:06:53.467 --> 00:06:57.767
baby I mean, really
catchy love songs,

00:06:57.767 --> 00:07:00.100
really quite--you know,
they're actually important

00:07:00.100 --> 00:07:05.200
in the history of the
evolution of rock music and

00:07:05.200 --> 00:07:10.767
the Motown sound.&nbsp; But
by--when we get into 1970,

00:07:10.767 --> 00:07:15.000
Gaye is
wrestling with, well,

00:07:15.000 --> 00:07:19.300
partly exhaustion
from churning out these

00:07:19.300 --> 00:07:23.300
saccharine-laden songs,
but also he's wrestling with

00:07:23.300 --> 00:07:24.567
what's going on
in the country,

00:07:24.567 --> 00:07:27.900
and he wants to aspire to do
something quite different.&nbsp;

00:07:27.900 --> 00:07:33.467
And he earns, secures
himself a new contract with

00:07:33.467 --> 00:07:35.600
Motown and he's
given creative license,

00:07:35.600 --> 00:07:37.900
which is astonishing.&nbsp; This
is the big sort of rupture

00:07:37.900 --> 00:07:40.600
in Motown.&nbsp; He's
given creative license,

00:07:40.600 --> 00:07:43.667
and he turns--and he
generates a concept album.&nbsp;

00:07:43.667 --> 00:07:49.200
The album's called What's
Going On?&nbsp; It's dealing with

00:07:49.200 --> 00:07:52.700
Vietnam, it's dealing
with economic despair,

00:07:52.700 --> 00:07:57.067
with incredible inflation
going on in the country.&nbsp;

00:07:57.067 --> 00:07:59.100
It's dealing with
ecological despair,

00:07:59.100 --> 00:08:01.700
and this is a few years
before Earth Day would

00:08:01.700 --> 00:08:03.900
actually take effect, when
people are wondering what

00:08:03.900 --> 00:08:07.900
we're doing to this
particular planet.&nbsp; In fact,

00:08:07.900 --> 00:08:12.000
I've often, when I've given
this lecture--and I wanted,

00:08:12.000 --> 00:08:14.300
I hadn't given a, a cultural
politics lecture for years,

00:08:14.300 --> 00:08:16.867
and I finally realized it
was time to do so.&nbsp; And I

00:08:16.867 --> 00:08:18.700
listened to What's Going On?

00:08:18.700 --> 00:08:20.000
Just to see if I
wanted to play a clip,

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:22.467
and I realized, I could
actually just put the CD on,

00:08:22.467 --> 00:08:24.500
leave the room, have
you guys understand the

00:08:24.500 --> 00:08:28.200
nineteen, early 1970s by the
time the album was over.&nbsp;

00:08:28.200 --> 00:08:33.100
But, well, I have to get up
and say something.&nbsp; So you

00:08:33.100 --> 00:08:36.700
have a moment of
escalating war in Vietnam,

00:08:36.700 --> 00:08:39.900
fear of, of
destruction of the planet,

00:08:39.900 --> 00:08:43.067
ecologically speaking,
environmentally speaking,

00:08:43.067 --> 00:08:44.900
hyperinflation in
the United States,

00:08:44.900 --> 00:08:52.300
poverty, urban decay.&nbsp; And
Marvin Gaye starts writing

00:08:52.300 --> 00:08:56.100
these pieces, or produces
these songs.&nbsp; They merge one

00:08:56.100 --> 00:08:57.500
into another in
What's Going On?

00:08:57.500 --> 00:08:59.600
and, in fact, if you do want
to learn about the 1970s,

00:08:59.600 --> 00:09:02.400
just go out and--I used to
say buy the album at the

00:09:02.400 --> 00:09:04.200
record store, then
you could buy the CD,

00:09:04.200 --> 00:09:06.467
and now it's just,
you know, go to iTunes,

00:09:06.467 --> 00:09:11.500
I suppose.&nbsp; Although you
should patronize Cutler's,

00:09:11.500 --> 00:09:19.500
the local record store.&nbsp;
[Students laugh]&nbsp; One of his

00:09:19.500 --> 00:09:21.700
signature songs
from the album,

00:09:21.700 --> 00:09:22.700
"What's Happening,
Brother?"&nbsp; It's the story of

00:09:22.700 --> 00:09:26.200
a returning vet,
comes back from Vietnam,

00:09:26.200 --> 00:09:29.700
trying to figure out what
is happening on the street,

00:09:29.700 --> 00:09:33.000
really trying to get back
into the mundane routine

00:09:33.000 --> 00:09:35.000
of life.

00:09:36.167 --> 00:09:37.167
I'll play a clip of it.

