a lament.&nbsp; Now if you think

00:13:17.100 --> 00:13:18.700
I'm stretching this
just a little bit,

00:13:18.700 --> 00:13:19.700
I mean, this is
just one album,

00:13:19.700 --> 00:13:23.600
after all, let me share with
you a personal story.&nbsp; It's

00:13:23.600 --> 00:13:28.767
happening in 1971, '72,
and '73.&nbsp; I was too young to

00:13:28.767 --> 00:13:33.300
remember it, actually,
but in 1990--let me think,

00:13:33.300 --> 00:13:37.100
when would this
have been--1997 or so,

00:13:37.100 --> 00:13:38.900
I was living in Los
Angeles.&nbsp; My father and

00:13:38.900 --> 00:13:42.700
mother had come to
visit me and my wife,

00:13:42.700 --> 00:13:44.600
and we're driving.&nbsp; We go
out to--he'd lived in L.A.

00:13:44.600 --> 00:13:48.200
for a while when--during
this era--we drive out to

00:13:48.200 --> 00:13:50.500
visit some old friends
of his in Los Angeles,

00:13:50.500 --> 00:13:52.800
have a great
night.&nbsp; Come back,

00:13:52.800 --> 00:13:55.200
we're driving back and I
happen just to put on this

00:13:55.200 --> 00:13:58.767
album.&nbsp; I listen to it all
the time.&nbsp; He and my mother

00:13:58.767 --> 00:14:00.700
riding in the back
seat and after a while,

00:14:00.700 --> 00:14:03.700
I realize what--something
doesn't sound quite right.&nbsp;

00:14:03.700 --> 00:14:06.200
And then I realize, what I'm
hearing in the back seat is

00:14:06.200 --> 00:14:10.567
weeping, I mean, flat out
weeping.&nbsp; I turn down the

00:14:10.567 --> 00:14:13.667
music, ask what's going
on, and my father just says,

00:14:13.667 --> 00:14:14.900
"I can't--you know,
I just can't talk,

00:14:14.900 --> 00:14:18.600
can't talk about it."&nbsp; Get
back to the house.&nbsp; I've

00:14:18.600 --> 00:14:21.367
never seen this guy cry in
my entire life.&nbsp; I don't

00:14:21.367 --> 00:14:24.600
know what, what has actually
happened.&nbsp; I sit down with

00:14:24.600 --> 00:14:25.667
him and my mother
says, "Wendell,

00:14:25.667 --> 00:14:27.267
just tell him what's
going--what happened

00:14:27.267 --> 00:14:29.800
there."&nbsp; And my
father essentially had a

00:14:29.800 --> 00:14:32.800
flashback.&nbsp; He was a
Vietnam vet himself,

00:14:32.800 --> 00:14:36.667
fought--flew in the Air
Force.&nbsp; And he's saying that

00:14:36.667 --> 00:14:38.200
album just brought
everything back.&nbsp; I mean,

00:14:38.200 --> 00:14:39.800
"You just don't, you
just don't understand,

00:14:39.800 --> 00:14:45.400
 he tells me, "what it was
like."&nbsp; People going off and

00:14:45.400 --> 00:14:47.900
trying to--risking their
lives for their country,

00:14:47.900 --> 00:14:50.500
and being treated the way
they were treated upon their

00:14:50.500 --> 00:14:52.600
return.&nbsp; And Marvin Gaye
really understood the sense

00:14:52.600 --> 00:14:54.800
of confusion
that many people,

00:14:54.800 --> 00:14:56.300
not just the vets, but
certainly in his case,

00:14:56.300 --> 00:14:58.700
the vets come back trying to
figure out what is going on

00:14:58.700 --> 00:15:02.000
in this country, what do
they actually fight for?&nbsp;

00:15:02.000 --> 00:15:05.900
Feeling a sense of moral
confusion as well.&nbsp; My

00:15:05.900 --> 00:15:07.300
father even
talked about the,

00:15:07.300 --> 00:15:10.200
you know, the economy and
the ecological landscape,

00:15:10.200 --> 00:15:11.400
all in that same
moment.&nbsp; He goes,

00:15:11.400 --> 00:15:15.100
"That album really captured
it all.&nbsp; Marvin Gaye

00:15:15.100 --> 00:15:21.100
understood what was
going on."&nbsp; Now this album,

00:15:27.000 --> 00:15:30.700
What's Going On?, fluctuates
between the international

00:15:30.700 --> 00:15:36.500
critique and also
things happening in U.S.

00:15:36.500 --> 00:15:40.000
cities, again, this
economic despair,

00:15:40.000 --> 00:15:41.600
I keep coming back to
it.&nbsp; It's really one of the

00:15:41.600 --> 00:15:46.467
defining elements of
the time.&nbsp; You also have,

00:15:46.467 --> 00:15:48.700
during this
moment, this rise of,

00:15:48.700 --> 00:15:52.600
in, in line with the
Black Panther Party,

00:15:52.600 --> 00:15:55.500
certainly, this rise of
a celebration of black

00:15:55.500 --> 00:16:01.367
masculinity, black virility,
and also black cultural

00:16:01.367 --> 00:16:03.700
celebration.&nbsp; Quite a
different one than the

00:16:03.700 --> 00:16:04.767
Harlem
Renaissance, certainly,

